postcontent: I made this for my son, but he hardly ever used it. Probably less than 200 arrow impacts total... and this target hardly even noticed that many 'hits'.   Is made with several dozen strips of carpet cut into roughly 4+ foot high by 1 foot deep strips, which are then compressed 'edge-wise' to form a very 'arrow friendly' impact surface.The strips are held together via (4) long threaded rods, which have very large nuts, and fender washers on the ends. The rods are threaded through a husky wood frame of 4 x 4 treated wood that compresses the carpet pieces side-to-side. The frame is located at the the top and bottom of the target area, out of the impact area. The entire target can be 'tension-ed'' (by screwing down the nuts tighter) to adjust for how hard your bow shoots.   THIS THING IS HEAVY! You'll either need 2 strong guys to move it intact, or else you'll need to disassemble it for relocation.   I built this target over 3 years ago... and it's still in great shape.
